description.value: “Mlada Srbadija” was a short-time published journal from January 1876. The owner and editor was Nikola Kapamadžija. The first issue from 1 January 1876 had a picture of Svetozar Miletić, the political leader of the Serbs in Vojvodina. The content was rich and manifold: texts from Jovan Stefanović Vilovski and Stjepan Mitrov Ljubiša, poems and biographies. The journal was planned to be published three times a month and printed in the Mechitarist Monastery printing house. Only three issues were published, all of them in January 1876.The address of the editorial office was Ottakringer Hauptstrasse 9, but the building does not exists anymore.

description.value: From 1917 to 1918 was Max von Milenković (Max Morold), writer and art critic of Serbian origin director of k.k. Hofburgtheater (Burgtheater) in Vienna.

The Mechitaristen Congregation established itself in Vienna since the 1770s. It founded a printing house in 1811, which was active until 1873. From the 1873 to 1876 printing house was in possession of Karl Seidl and Felix Mayer. This printing house is of greatest value for the history of Serbian literacy: it was the first printing house in the world with Vuk Karadzić’s orthography (30 letters) and his “Riječnik” (1818) was printed as the first book in history with this new orthography. The building still exists.

description.value: In the year 1792 Josef von Kurzböck (1736-1792) sold his printing house to Stefan von Novaković for 25,000 forints. Although Novaković was only owner for three years, his contribution to the history of Serbian publishing was enormous. Among other books, he printed one of the first Serbian history books of the historian and Archimandrite Jovan Rajić (1726-1801) in 1794/95 entitled "History of the Bulgarian, Serbian and Croatian Peoples" ("Историја разних славенских народов, наипаче Болгар, Хорватов и Сербов"). Stefan von Novaković sold his printing house to Pest University in 1795. His printing house was in Salvatorgasse 456 (1010 Vienna), which was after renumeration house No. 6. The building does not exist anymore.

Staaten"; in Slavonic-Serbian entitled "Нѣмецкïй и сербскïй словарь на потребу сербскагo народа в ъкрал. Державахъ") was printed in 1791 in the printing house of Josef Kurzböck (1736-1792), where Avramović was proofreader for Cyrillic books since 1786. It was located between today´s Maysedergasse, Neuer Markt, Kärntner Straße and Lobkowitzplatz. Schmidbauer´s son Josef continued to work in the printing house after father´s death.

description.value: Zaharije Jovanović – Čiča (1810-1850), one of the Serbian leaders in the war against the Hungarians in 1848/49,  died in the House No 8 auf der Wieden (today Wiedner Hauptstraße 14) on 18 November 1850 at the age of 40. Jovanović was buried two days later in the Orthodox part of the St. Marx cemetery in Vienna.

description.value: In this building was from 1843 to 1846 a silk store “zum Fürsten Milosch“. The owner was Vasilije Aleksić, a friend and business partner of Prince Miloš Obrenović.
